[
    {
        "content": "<p>[It seems this is the best place where to advertise this, so I'm gonna have to start my thread here!]<br>\nSo I bit the bullet and started a curated list of material about double categories <span aria-label=\"cat\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f408\" role=\"img\" title=\"cat\">:cat:</span><span aria-label=\"cat\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f408\" role=\"img\" title=\"cat\">:cat:</span>, with particular focus on the recent wave of applications (it's insane how much stuff came out this year only??)</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/mattecapu/awesome-double-categories\">https://github.com/mattecapu/awesome-double-categories</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It's still very far from complete, so please contribute! (if you don't know how to use PRs, just open an issue with the stuff you'd like to see added, or DM me here)</p>",
        "id": 304256454,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1665880756
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nice!  Some or all of this could also be added to the nLab <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/double%20category\">[[double category]]</a> page.</p>",
        "id": 304256831,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1665881172
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> , you lost a perfect occasion to entitle your document \"Prepare for trouble, make it double\"! <a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/hFx-0qQ_GqeNCTi_zJb_YJAd/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/hFx-0qQ_GqeNCTi_zJb_YJAd/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/hFx-0qQ_GqeNCTi_zJb_YJAd/image.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 304278301,
        "sender_full_name": "fosco",
        "timestamp": 1665906594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span>: instead of adding a link to the GitHub repository on the nLab page, why not simply update the nLab page with all of the references? Creating a separate repository just means there are now two places people need to check for references instead of one.</p>",
        "id": 304294225,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1665917899
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here is an application in robotics/hybrid systems:<br>\n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.01267\">https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.01267</a></p>",
        "id": 304300000,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1665921495
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Question: How do double cats behave wrt implementation? I honestly don't know and I'm curious!</p>",
        "id": 304312879,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1665929078
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What do you mean by \"implementation\"?</p>",
        "id": 304314135,
        "sender_full_name": "Jacques Carette",
        "timestamp": 1665929965
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If I have a  double-categorical model of some sort, is there an established set of best practices to bring it to, say, Haskell or Rust in a performant way?</p>",
        "id": 304314747,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1665930176
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For instance, open games and  decorated/structured cospans have been quite popular also because producing software suites relying on those formalisms has been largely feasible. So you can move from 'ideas on paper' to 'i'm running my ideas on a computer'.  What I am asking is at what point we are wrt this when it comes to double categories</p>",
        "id": 304314921,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1665930282
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276438\">Fabrizio Genovese</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/274877-practice.3A-our-work/topic/Matteo.20Capucci/near/304314747\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If I have a  double-categorical model of some sort, is there an established set of best practices to bring it to, say, Haskell or Rust in a performant way?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It can also be non-performant for now btw, I'm just curious to know if there's work in this direction</p>",
        "id": 304314978,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1665930338
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Aha, thanks for the answer, as it wasn't the one that I expected (and would have involved Coq/Agda/Idris/Isabelle...)</p>",
        "id": 304315983,
        "sender_full_name": "Jacques Carette",
        "timestamp": 1665930996
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm an applications guy after all lol</p>",
        "id": 304316821,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1665931603
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's sort of a subset of Kenny's thesis, but there's this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>John Baez and Kenny Courser, Structured cospans, <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.04630\">https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.04630</a></li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 304329856,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1665939891
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's like the prequel to \"Structured and decorated cospans\" - it introduced double categories of structured cospans.</p>",
        "id": 304340360,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1665946143
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In addition to my papers on gradual typing that Dan linked to on twitter (and here's a blog post about the first one: <a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2018/02/gradual_typing.html\">https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2018/02/gradual_typing.html</a>)), an earlier \"PL\" application of pro-arrow equipments was this paper:  <a href=\"https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.5555/2591370.2591396\">https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.5555/2591370.2591396</a></p>",
        "id": 304353004,
        "sender_full_name": "Max New",
        "timestamp": 1665955763
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My ex-student Roald Koudenburg has written on various aspects of double categories.  See his <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/search/math?searchtype=author&amp;query=Koudenburg%2C+S+R\">arXiv page</a>.</p>",
        "id": 304432628,
        "sender_full_name": "Simon Willerton",
        "timestamp": 1666004465
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for everyone's suggestions!</p>",
        "id": 304495830,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1666021651
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276092\">@Nathanael Arkor</span> that's a good point, my rationale was that the attitudes of the two resources are different. At least I wanted to recapitulate applications of double categories more than material on double categories themselves. Of course some basic concepts are useful. It's hard to make a distinction.</p>",
        "id": 304496192,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1666021754
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not that I'm against merging it in the nLab, but shoving everything at the end of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/double%20category\">[[double category]]</a> feels sub-optimal</p>",
        "id": 304496381,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1666021804
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You could make a separate page on <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/applications%20of%20double%20categories\">[[applications of double categories]]</a>, perhaps.</p>",
        "id": 304496440,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1666021822
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh if that's a legal move, that sounds like a great synthesis</p>",
        "id": 304496538,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1666021852
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Then it could also include direct links to the nLab pages about the relevant concepts, like <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/structured%20cospans\">[[structured cospans]]</a>.</p>",
        "id": 304496549,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1666021854
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Will do asap (so maybe in a couple of days)</p>",
        "id": 304496599,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1666021869
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I followed <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span>'s suggestions and wrote <a href=\"https://www.localcharts.org/t/categories-are-monads-in-spans/11397\">a small explainer</a> about 'categories as monads in spans'. I started with a more ambitious post on 'actions of double categories' and then resized the scope until I got something I could write in less than a couple of hours. Well, I'm just happy I did it :)</p>",
        "id": 404594747,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1701167105
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great!   This is a very beautiful fact, I don't think I've seen anyone write a friendly explanation before.</p>",
        "id": 404638103,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1701178944
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>In fact, this very trick is used to define and accomunate different flavours of categories: just take monads in a suitable bicategory.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There's no word \"accomunate\" in English, or at least it's very rare.   I'm not quite sure what's the right replacement.</p>",
        "id": 404638252,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1701179003
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\"Accommodate\"?</p>",
        "id": 404647321,
        "sender_full_name": "Todd Trimble",
        "timestamp": 1701181754
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>'unify', maybe</p>",
        "id": 404648614,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathaniel Virgo",
        "timestamp": 1701182125
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes I think \"relate\" or \"unify\" are good.  \"Accomunare\" means something like \"group together\" or, literally, \"make two (or more) things have something in common\".</p>",
        "id": 404648835,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Mazza",
        "timestamp": 1701182188
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/274877-community.3A-our-work/topic/Matteo.20Capucci/near/404638252\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In fact, this very trick is used to define and accomunate different flavours of categories: just take monads in a suitable bicategory.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There's no word \"accomunate\" in English, or at least it's very rare.   I'm not quite sure what's the right replacement.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Uh, thanks for spotting. <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276839\">@Damiano Mazza</span> got it right, I mistranslated from Italian. There doesn't seem to be a perfect translation, I think I'll go with 'relate'.</p>",
        "id": 404658844,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1701185030
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I should advertise my blogging here.</p>\n<p>Today <a href=\"https://www.localcharts.org/t/reflections-from-factorization-systems/13111\">I posted</a> a very elementary wrote up of the very basics of factorization systems in order to record the proof that an <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/orthogonal%20factorization%20system\">[[orthogonal factorization system]]</a> on a category with a terminal objecto yields a reflective subcategory thereof.<br>\nSome days ago I also wrote down a proof of a fact I have known for a while but kept misremembering, namely that <a href=\"https://www.localcharts.org/t/tambara-modules-are-modules/12745\">Tambara modules are modules</a>, i.e. that the free Tambara module monad is a monad of free modules.</p>",
        "id": 411255199,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1704399471
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Suggestions and corrections are welcome!</p>",
        "id": 411255242,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1704399483
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> has localcharts moved around a bit? I cannot read your blog post.</p>",
        "id": 538033960,
        "sender_full_name": "Valeria de Paiva",
        "timestamp": 1757195316
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"280755\">@Owen Lynch</span> shut down the website :( I should get around moving the posts over to my own blog. There is an archive <a href=\"https://localcharts.org/archive.html\">here</a> in the meantime</p>",
        "id": 538037188,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1757199689
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's about time I start posting here lol... Here's some recent output!</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Me and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"751249\">@David Jaz Myers</span> recently updated <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2510.23531\">our preprint on 2-classifiers in 2-categories of 2-algebras</a>, following a very helpful review. They found a mistake which brought us to substantially alter the proof strategy for the main theorem, and surrender to work with lax/pseudo T-algebras rater than strict ones (not much is lost if you can strictify the 2-classifier anyway, as it often is the case). This new proof is <em>much</em> nicer though, and about as long.</li>\n<li>With David again, we sent <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.03017\">Compositionality of Lyapunov functions via assume-guarantee reasoning</a> to ACT, which got accepted. It is a proof-of-concept paper showing how assume-guarantee verification for Moore machines emerges basically for free out of the DOTS yoga, and with minimal tweaking one can extend it to (ISS) Lyapunov certificates.</li>\n<li>Finally, after two years of work on quantitative logic, me and others from the pertinent ARIA collaboration are have put out some stuff about Quantitative Linear Logic (QLL) and its applications. You can read about them <a href=\"https://matteocapucci.eu/two-preprints-in-quantitative-logic/\">on my blog</a>. I'm very excited about this work, whose primary aim is to bridge structural (meaning categorical and logical) and quantitative (meaning statistical and analytical) methods.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Comments, questions, and ideas are welcome!</p>",
        "id": 595608965,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1779020624
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Congratulations on the papers to you both, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275932\">@Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"751249\">@David Jaz Myers</span> , as well as for having it accepted to ACT. I've been especially looking forward to the paper on the double category of certified systems since the first DOTS paper mentioned this area as future work, it's great to see it out:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Our approach begins with the observation that assume–guarantee reasoning is, for certain specifications, highly reminiscent of the definition of a Moore machine. A Moore machine with action set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> and observation set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">O</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">O</span></span></span></span> consists of a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">S</span></span></span></span> of states together with two functions: the view <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">v : S \\to O</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0359em;\">v</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">O</span></span></span></span> yielding an output symbol and the update <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>u</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">u : S \\times I \\to S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">u</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">S</span></span></span></span> transitioning the state on receiving an input. Suppose we have a predicate <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>φ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\varphi(s)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">φ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> telling us which states <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s \\in S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">S</span></span></span></span> are \"safe\"; our aim is to prove that when starting in a safe state we remain in a safe state so long as our input <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i\\in I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6986em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">I</span></span></span></span> always satisfies its assumptions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha(i)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. We also provide a guarantee <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>γ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>o</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\gamma(o)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0556em;\">γ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> on output symbols <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>o</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">o\\in O</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">o</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">O</span></span></span></span>, which holds under the assumption that we are in a safe state. In total, we analyze assume–guarantee for state-safety specifications as the pair of implications</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mtable rowspacing=\"0.16em\" columnalign=\"center\" columnspacing=\"1em\"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>u</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>v</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow><mo>⊨</mo><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mtable rowspacing=\"0.16em\" columnalign=\"center\" columnspacing=\"1em\"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>φ</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>φ</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow><mo>⇆</mo><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mtable rowspacing=\"0.16em\" columnalign=\"center\" columnspacing=\"1em\"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>α</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>γ</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟺</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">{</mo><mtable rowspacing=\"0.36em\" columnalign=\"left left\" columnspacing=\"1em\"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mrow><mi>φ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∧</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⇒</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>φ</mi><mo fence=\"true\" stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"1.2em\" maxsize=\"1.2em\">(</mo><mi>u</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>i</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo fence=\"true\" stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"1.2em\" maxsize=\"1.2em\">)</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mrow><mi>φ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⇒</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>γ</mi><mo fence=\"true\" stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"1.2em\" maxsize=\"1.2em\">(</mo><mi>v</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo fence=\"true\" stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"1.2em\" maxsize=\"1.2em\">)</mo></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\begin{pmatrix} u \\\\[4pt] v \\end{pmatrix}\\vDash\\begin{pmatrix} \\varphi \\\\[4pt] \\varphi \\end{pmatrix}\\leftrightarrows\\begin{pmatrix} \\alpha \\\\[4pt] \\gamma \\end{pmatrix}\\iff\\begin{cases}\\varphi(s)\\wedge \\alpha(i)\\;\\Rightarrow\\; \\varphi\\bigl(u(s,i)\\bigr),\\\\[6pt]\\varphi(s)\\;\\Rightarrow\\; \\gamma\\bigl(v(s)\\bigr)\\end{cases}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:3em;vertical-align:-1.25em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size4\">(</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mtable\"><span class=\"col-align-c\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.65em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.81em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">u</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.21em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0359em;\">v</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size4\">)</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊨</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:3em;vertical-align:-1.25em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size4\">(</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mtable\"><span class=\"col-align-c\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.65em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.81em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">φ</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.21em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">φ</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size4\">)</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⇆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:3em;vertical-align:-1.25em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size4\">(</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mtable\"><span class=\"col-align-c\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.65em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.81em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.21em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0556em;\">γ</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size4\">)</span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟺</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:3.6em;vertical-align:-1.55em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen\"><span class=\"delimsizing mult\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:2.05em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.15em;\"></span><span class=\"delimsizinginner delim-size4\"><span>⎩</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.492em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.15em;\"></span><span style=\"height:0.016em;width:0.8889em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"0.8889em\" height=\"0.016em\" style=\"width:0.8889em\" viewBox=\"0 0 888.89 16\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMinYMin\"><path d=\"M384 0 H504 V16 H384z M384 0 H504 V16 H384z\"/></svg></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.15em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.15em;\"></span><span class=\"delimsizinginner delim-size4\"><span>⎨</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-4.292em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.15em;\"></span><span style=\"height:0.016em;width:0.8889em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"0.8889em\" height=\"0.016em\" style=\"width:0.8889em\" viewBox=\"0 0 888.89 16\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMinYMin\"><path d=\"M384 0 H504 V16 H384z M384 0 H504 V16 H384z\"/></svg></span></span><span style=\"top:-4.3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.15em;\"></span><span class=\"delimsizinginner delim-size4\"><span>⎧</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.55em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mtable\"><span class=\"col-align-l\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.99em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.99em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.008em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">φ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∧</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇒</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">φ</span><span class=\"mopen\"><span class=\"delimsizing size1\">(</span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">u</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"delimsizing size1\">)</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-1.95em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.008em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">φ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇒</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0556em;\">γ</span><span class=\"mopen\"><span class=\"delimsizing size1\">(</span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0359em;\">v</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"delimsizing size1\">)</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.49em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>These have almost the same form as the functions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>u</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">u : S \\times I \\to S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">u</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0785em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">S</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">v : S \\to O</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0359em;\">v</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">O</span></span></span></span>. In fact, we can see assume–guarantee certified Moore machines (for state-safety specifications) as Moore machines in another category — this time, a category of sets equipped with a predicate, rather than just sets in the un-certified case.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That's (a part of) the DOTS yoga <span aria-label=\"relieved\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f60c\" role=\"img\" title=\"relieved\">:relieved:</span> That's the microcosm  <span aria-label=\"relieved\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f60c\" role=\"img\" title=\"relieved\">:relieved:</span></p>\n<p>This is, if I'm not mistaken, the first paper to use DOTS since <em><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.18329\">Towards a double operadic theory of systems</a></em> by Sophie Libkind and David Jaz Myers introduced it. Beyond developing double categories of certified systems, it helps to get a better picture of what using DOTS looks like in a paper and how it can be introduced to readers, which is especially helpful for someone like myself who's still learning but can't help but want to enter the DOTS yoga.</p>\n<p>A question that comes up is: Moore machines compose by setting parameters according to variables of state or what SL and DJM call the <em>parameter setting paradigm</em>. Is assume-guarantee reasoning possible for other paradigms of composition such as the <em>port-plugging paradigm</em> or the <em>variable sharing paradigm</em>? And is there any idea what some of the double categories of certified systems would look like for other paradigms of composition?</p>",
        "id": 596737677,
        "sender_full_name": "V Slicer",
        "timestamp": 1779369875
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"1070312\">@V Slicer</span> for the kind words!</p>",
        "id": 596747783,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1779372072
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"1070312\">V Slicer</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/274877-community.3A-our-work/topic/Matteo.20Capucci/near/596737677\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Is assume-guarantee reasoning possible for other paradigms of composition such as the <em>port-plugging paradigm</em> or the <em>varabiable sharing paradigm</em>?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Indeed, one of the main points of the paper is that fibrations of algebras of systems are a natural semantics for 'compositional logic', with the latter taking a different form depending on the kind of compositionality your systems have,. Assume-guarantee reasoning seems to have the form of parameter-setting.<br>\nNow what could e.g. port-plugging look like? I have a strong feeling it will be related to regular logic and thus <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1811.00420\">behavioural mereology</a>.</p>",
        "id": 596751021,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1779372813
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you feel like entering the DOTSverse, this might be a cool project</p>",
        "id": 596751088,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1779372827
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'll also refer you to <a href=\"https://matteocapucci.eu/assets/2024/09/goals.pdf\">these old notes of mine</a> about compositional predicate logic</p>",
        "id": 596751306,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1779372871
    }
]